00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:21,360
can use to talk about business strategy.
You’ll learn useful language to talk\h\h

5
00:00:21,360 --> 00:00:27,680
about losing market share, entering\h
a new market, launching new products,\h\h

6
00:00:27,680 --> 00:00:31,312
and staying competitive in an evolving market.

7
00:00:35,520 --> 00:00:40,160
Hello, everyone, and thanks for joining us for\h
this conference call, wherever you might happen\h\h

8
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:46,720
to be in the world! If you don’t know, my name’s\h
Dimitri, and I lead the marketing department.\h\h

9
00:00:47,520 --> 00:00:52,160
I’m not sure that you’re aware, but our European\h
business has not been doing well in the last\h\h

10
00:00:52,160 --> 00:00:59,520
year or so. In particular, we’ve been losing\h
market share to our rivals. A Korean company,\h\h

11
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:04,800
Neidon, entered the European market three\h
years ago, and have adopted an aggressive\h\h

12
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:11,840
pricing strategy, which is putting pressure on\h
our revenues. Additionally, a German start-up,\h\h

13
00:01:11,840 --> 00:01:16,480
called Hammer, have expanded their market\h
share in Germany, Austria and Switzerland,\h\h

14
00:01:16,480 --> 00:01:22,080
partially at our expense. It’s clear that\h
we need to respond to these market forces,\h\h

15
00:01:22,080 --> 00:01:25,840
and I’d like to start thinking about\h
our options during this meeting.\h

16
00:01:26,880 --> 00:01:33,600
In this presentation, you heard some phrases based\h
on the word ‘market’. Let’s look at a few of them.\h

17
00:01:36,080 --> 00:01:41,440
Imagine that you want to explain the meaning of\h
these phrases in English. What would you say?\h

18
00:01:44,080 --> 00:01:48,720
If you’re losing market share, then your\h
business has a smaller proportion of\h\h

19
00:01:48,720 --> 00:01:53,840
the available customers. The phrase in\h
sentence two has the opposite meaning;\h\h

20
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:58,960
if you expand your market share, you reach\h
a higher proportion of potential customers.

21
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:04,800
You can also gain market share,\h
which has the same meaning.\h

22
00:02:07,520 --> 00:02:15,120
‘Market forces’ – you can also say ‘market\h
pressures’ – describes the conditions in a market,\h\h

23
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:18,480
and how they affect company\h
behaviour and strategy.

24
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:23,200
For example, a market in a particular field,\h\h

25
00:02:23,200 --> 00:02:30,320
or a particular area, might get more or\h
less competitive with time. Consumers there\h\h

26
00:02:30,320 --> 00:02:38,000
might get richer or poorer. These are examples of\h
market forces which businesses need to adapt to.\h

27
00:02:40,640 --> 00:02:45,040
Generally, you can improve your English to\h
talk about these topics by paying attention\h\h

28
00:02:45,040 --> 00:02:50,640
to *collocations*. A collocation is when\h
you use words in a specific combination.

29
00:02:51,520 --> 00:02:57,840
‘Expand your market share’ is a collocation.\h
You might know all these words individually,\h\h

30
00:02:57,840 --> 00:03:03,520
but could you use them together? With\h
collocations, you need to learn the\h\h

31
00:03:03,520 --> 00:03:08,400
combination of words as a single block, so that\h
you can use them together without thinking.

